From: Chris Kohn <chris.kohn@amd.com>
Subject: [PATCH] qt_gui_cpp_sip: Fix Python extension suffix for cross-compilation

When cross-compiling, the native Python interpreter returns the host
architecture in EXT_SUFFIX (e.g., x86_64-linux-gnu) instead of the
target architecture (e.g., aarch64-linux-gnu). This causes the
generated .so file to have an incorrect name that Python cannot import
on the target.

Use the PYTHON_SOABI CMake variable passed by the Yocto build system
to construct the correct extension suffix when cross-compiling.

AI-Generated: Claude claude-opus-4-6
Signed-off-by: Chris Kohn <chris.kohn@amd.com>

diff --git a/src/qt_gui_cpp_sip/CMakeLists.txt b/src/qt_gui_cpp_sip/CMakeLists.txt
--- a/src/qt_gui_cpp_sip/CMakeLists.txt
+++ b/src/qt_gui_cpp_sip/CMakeLists.txt
@@ -90,10 +90,16 @@ if(sip_helper_FOUND)
     DEPENDENCIES qt_gui_cpp
   )
 
-  execute_process(
-    COMMAND ${Python3_EXECUTABLE} -c "import sysconfig as c; print(c.get_config_var('EXT_SUFFIX'), end='')"
-    OUTPUT_VARIABLE PYTHON_EXTENSION_MODULE_SUFFIX
-    ERROR_QUIET)
+  # When cross-compiling, use PYTHON_SOABI passed by the build system
+  # instead of querying the native Python interpreter
+  if(CMAKE_CROSSCOMPILING AND DEFINED PYTHON_SOABI)
+    set(PYTHON_EXTENSION_MODULE_SUFFIX ".${PYTHON_SOABI}.so")
+  else()
+    execute_process(
+      COMMAND ${Python3_EXECUTABLE} -c "import sysconfig as c; print(c.get_config_var('EXT_SUFFIX'), end='')"
+      OUTPUT_VARIABLE PYTHON_EXTENSION_MODULE_SUFFIX
+      ERROR_QUIET)
+  endif()
 
   if(APPLE)
     set(LIBQT_GUI_CPP_SIP_SUFFIX .so)
